m/ucaulfield.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Caulfield</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/21/01 6:10:44 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> How much am I missing?</span><hr size=1> The person who introduced me to Everquest was a big PvP fan. He originally came from UO and then migrated over. His favorite character was a 35 druid on Rallos, his server of choice (he had higher lvl chars, but he said on Rallos 35 was the fun lvl range for him). He has since quit EQ completely for AO and WWII.<br>
<br>
Because of this however, my first EQ characters were of course, created on Rallos Zek. I learned alot there (not about PKing or PvPing really, but about the atmosphere of a zek). I liked it that the enemies which I fought against and which wanted me dead weren't all just bits of code, and that there were consequences to my actions which directly affected me.<br>
<br>
Throughout my short EQ lifespan, I've banded together with friends on Rallos to hunt down a griefer in Ro. I've run loot and goods between rival guilds as a bard. I've gone on raids in Sullon against those short arrogant dwarves of Kaladim. I've defended Faydwer from massive Iksar and Dark Elf invasions. And I have argued and dabated countless times online about the definitions of &quot;griefers&quot;, &quot;roleplayers&quot;, &quot;dishonor&quot; and &quot;neutral&quot;.<br>
<br>
These are things I never thought possible in a blue server. This, coupled with the fact that most blue servers are ultra crowded kept me from ever trying them out. Lately tho I can't help but wonder how much I am missing. We all know that PvP is fun, challenging, and intensely immersive. But so many state that it is also so flawwed and always shall be because EQ was not designed for PvP. So I gotta ask, what is it I am missing out on by never having played on a non-PvP server that I can't experience on a PvP server? I just want to know that I am not some biased shortsighted hypocrite when I switch to Shadowbane and say how much better it is compared to &quot;that damn unbalanced Verant game&quot;.<br>
<br>
Please fight the urge to respond with &quot;yer not missing anything man! all carebear servers are overcrowded with twinked bluebie farmers who camp all the good spawns 24-7! Zeks rule! PvP forever!&quot; Heh, as funny as that is, I'm actually looking for some constructive responses.<br>
<br>
,Caulfield<br>
20th High Elf Mage of Mithaniel Marr<br>
Sullon Zek <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=FAEBD7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/usintztp.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SintzTP</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/21/01 6:30:36 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How much am I missing?</span><hr size=1> &lt;-------  As you can tell I mostly played on a blue sever (and a bit on TZ, but nothing significant).  You're not really missing anything, unless you're one of those people that gets worked up or frustrated easily on SZ.<br>
<br>
That's about it, blue servers (at least TP) have a much more friendly environment as a whole, at least at the lower level tiers.  However, it can be a bit harder to make &quot;good friends&quot; on blue servers because you don't go through the same BS together that you do on SZ.<br>
<br>
I also find server politics on blue servers to be much more sickening, as they tend to be petty IMO.<br>
<br>
&quot;Move aside or my guild will camp the s@#t outta mob X and your's will never get into plane Y again!&quot;<br>
<br>
At least here you can do something about it.<br>
<br>
The only other thing I could think of is that it's much easier to get nice equipment on blue servers (at least compared to being on the good team now) than it is here.  So if you get really excited about getting the pHaT l3wTz you might wanna check out a mature blue server.<br>
<br>
Just my 2cps. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/umorganti.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Morganti</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tavern Regular</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/21/01 7:53:46 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How much am I missing?</span><hr size=1> well... did you watch one life to live this morning?<br>
me either... got better things to do. <p>"You can take me out back and shoot me but I will be damned if I agree with you."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=FAEBD7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/uwessrainkeeper.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wess Rainkeeper</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/21/01 8:11:27 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How much am I missing?</span><hr size=1> Well, loot is very easy to come by. My little brother often make new characters on random servers and an hour later they have full bronze and kunark quested weapon. Guild politics are very fierce and complicated. High level loot zones are off limits unless you reserved it in advance (Example: Planes runs are planned and checked for availability about a month or two in advance) One of the biggest offense on blue servers is Kill Stealing. Of course most of its just talk. The only thing they can do is train you, but that’s gets them &quot;warnings&quot;. Its basically two guilds shouting &quot;Well...fuck you!&quot; Then the other guild shouting back &quot;No, fuck you!&quot; (Well, in a symbolic sense).<br>
<br>
Hope that helps. <br>
 <p>Wess Rainkeeper - RETIRED : Bompenseiro Moltisanit - RETIRED | Whales, Erudite Paladin, Active.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/uvachir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vachir</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tavern Regular</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/21/01 9:00:06 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How much am I missing?</span><hr size=1> I haven't played on a blue server since TZ came up, but from what I remember the difference is that things are much more casual, people arn't in any hurry to do anything and the most complex thing you'll have to deal with is looting rules and raid schedules.  The part that got to me was that there was really no point to anything.  On SZ, when I got my RBF, I thought 'cool, now I can beat that druid into the ground next time they try and snare me', on a blue server it's really just something nice with no real purpose other than to get you to a higher level (so that you can get more gear and level more to get more gear and...).  People are very worried about having the 'best' items, not because they really need them but because then they can show how much more uber they are than everyone else, where on SZ, you are trying to get the best stuff you can because it gives you that much better chance at killing rather than being killed.<br>
<br>
Also skill is completely irrelivant, it doesn't matter how effective you are at playing your class, if you're a tank and you can hit things, you're just as good as any other tank, if you're a cleric who keeps people healed, that's just great, if you're a monk who can pull welcome to the club.  Granted better players will die a little less, level a little faster and be able to get gear a little easier but for the most part even a total moron will still do fine leveling from 1 to 60 where on SZ they wouldn't have made it very far when they realized they were being PKed constantly by even cons and had no idea how to fight back.<br>
<br>
There is something to be said for the PvE aspects of EQ, questing, exploring, raiding, but these are things that can be so much more rewarding on a PvP server.  Some people try PvP and don't like it, to them I would say stay where you are and play the game you like.. but if you've ever enjoyed giving someone a free trip to their bind point you can never go back. <p>--------------------<BR>
